title: Trinus Extruder Cooling Fan Shroud Version 2

description.text:
***UPDATED 8/16/2017** - It was pointed out to me that the original design of V2 caused the x axis to jam against the wire cable hook at the extreme right of it's travel. I've redesigned the cable management to eliminate this issue. Be sure to tuck the cable tightly behind the guide and into the hook, and avoid any wire ties around the cable from being oriented so as to catch on the x axis end plate.

This is version 2 of my extruder shroud. I always intended to redo it to a closer fit, but it took a while to get back to it. This version doesn't require any velcro, double sided tape, hooks or spring arms. It slides perfectly over the right side of the extruder, and has an integral hook to hold the wires out of the way.

I also included two holes to utilize the extruder's original wire tie location a way to absolutely fix this in place, but it does require some fidgeting. Using the smallest wire tie, insert the tie from the right through the slot in the extruder and fish it out the top hole. Then slip the wire tie 'box' end through the round hole in the shroud and the flat 'tail' end through the ellipse hole in the collar. Loosely close the tie, push the shroud in place and align the wire bundle under the hook. Finally, pull the wire tie tight and you are done. The rest of this summary is from the original.

I was having a problem with filament softening in the extruder housing and bending, creating jams. Kodama chose to piggyback the parts cooling fan onto the extruder cooling fan, which resulted in insufficient air flow through the extruder. This shroud positions a fan to draw air through the extruder housing and out the side exhaust. Its still a work in progress, as the shroud requires a piece of velcro on the top of the extruder housing and under the hook to stay in place. Creating a bow in the hook and extending the sides around the extruder housing will fix that, but I won't have time for a while, hence the velcro.

In using the shroud while printing a model that takes up the entire bed, I found that the wires from the extruder need to be routed over the output end of the fan using wire ties, as shown in the new picture above. As I'm using a low velocity fan, it doesn't impede the airflow significantly. If the wires are routed on the axis side of the shroud, they can catch on the end of the axis. If routed on the outside of the shroud, they overstretch the wire connections. I've also used wire ties to minimize the pulling of the connectors at the PCB end. I'm going to include wire management clips on the next version to avoid this issue.

I find sliding doors to be a pain because the closet is always only half open. A curtain works much better. Where you could just use a curtain rod, I like using the existing door channels. Tons of tapestries available on amazon that work great. Here's the one I chose.

To assemble the print you need to slide the bushings in place, and press the retaining caps into the holes using an arbor press, or like me, just a flat board. It takes quite a bit of force, but that's how they stay in place.

The clips get slid into the base one at a time loosely, sliding the curtain cloth into the jaws of the clips. Once the curtain is in the clip you can press the clip into the body. The taper with case the clips to tighten on the cloth, holding it in place even under tension.

description.text:
All hail the God-Emperor, may his guidance always protect us from the encroachment of the Heretics.

Directed by the Omnissiah to create this symbol of office, I made it needlessly complex by making the gemstone mount removable, in theory meaning that I could replace it with a different gemstone shape, such as a teardrop for Blood Angels, or whatever. It should also make it easier to print/finish/paint in parts, so the gemstone, the gemstone mount, and the badge could all be printed in different ways, and different filaments with any simple printer, then painted as needed with a minimum of masking needed.

I didn't find an Imperialis (winged skull) that fit my desires, so I made some wings and found a good skull. I've uploaded the wings in case someone has a need for them.

Printer:

Folger Tech Kossel rev B

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.05mm

Notes:

It looks better than I thought, but the little skulls look a lot like I took a spare rosarius off of a sprue and dragged a corner until it was real sized. The threaded gem holder didn't screw in for me - probably a combination of the fact that my printer slowly makes things smaller the higher up they go, the base of the screw squshed out, and I printed these in ABS with no cooling fan so there was some sag in the Z layers of the screw, some curl in the screw, and at least a little shrink in the screw hole. You know, ABS stuff. I would just scale down the screw a little bit in the X/Y to make it slot in without screwing, and pretend that the threads are there to make your CA glue work better at holding it together. Similarly scale down the gemstone (obviously). Good news is that a little trial and error with the gemstone and mount will take very little time and plastic.

I'm printing this thing super thin to reduce the post-processing necessary. I'd go thinner if I thought it would help, but mostly the finest detail is lost just because it's not being hand carved and molded. Honestly printing the wings as solid blocks and carving them down with a sharp exacto is the only way to do justice. I'm not that handy with a blade, so this is the next best thing.

Maybe in 30 years when we are looking at this design with our monitors 10x the resolution of human sight and using our 0.00001mm resolution 3D printers, this will be a perfect model for a Games Workshop bankruptcy party costume.

title: Lisam LS210 (QAV210) Mods: Compact, Stylish, Expandable.

description.text:
These are the mods I've performed on my budget racing quadcopter. It's based around the super budget Lisam LS210 frame, and makes it smaller, lighter, and much cooler looking. It consists of:

  1. A battery plate, which elevates the battery so it can sit on top of the receiver and half of the flight controller. It takes the place of the two aluminium standoffs at the back of the quad.
  2. A top plate, which covers the electronics, and the battery. Mounts to the front four standoffs, and holds all three antennas, and retains the battery.
  3. Antenna holder, which holds the two receiver antennas at a good angle, in the slots in the top cover.
  4. Front shrouds, these slide over the front standoffs, and cover your FPV electronics.
  5. ESC covers, these improve airflow, protect solder joints, and make the quad look better. Clips over the frame, but tape is recommended for installation.
  6. Feet, to go over the four shorter standoffs on the bottom. I screwed mine in with PC case screws, and the long end of the foot goes in between the motor screws.
  7. Battery clip holder, these mount to the rear screws, and the two rear screws that hold your board stack. They provide a point for the battery locking plate to hold on to.
  8. Battery locking plate, clips onto the top cover, and battery clip holders. This will hold a medium capacity 4S battery, or a higher capacity 3S battery. I'm using a cheap ZOP power 1800mah 4S.

Other notes:

I put produce rubber bands around the battery, to give the battery plate and top cover something to hold on to. Added some grey electrical tape on some parts, partly to hold the ESC covers on, and mostly for the EXTREME speed increase that comes with racing stripes. The camera mount is 25 degrees, but just give me a shout if you want a 30 degree version. Shouldn't be too hard to install, but if you need it I can make a video.

Happy Flying!

First off, let me please ask that if you like these designs and find them useful please do like, follow and share my content. And if you have any ideas or concepts to modify the content I would love to hear!

Update: The 52mm wheel uses 3mm bolts throughout. I also widened the hub, increased the size of the rollers and improved the threaded hub insert for both wheel sizes.

I recommend printing the 67mm wheel prior to trying the smaller wheel. It would be great to see what would be capable with a SLA/DLP resin type printer. I envisage some neat variants of the main body to reduce material usage.

In the works is a two part roller that can be printed in two materials ( eg. plastic and ninja flex) in order to produce a solid roller body with an outer that would have greater grip. I have removed the "work in progress" tag, though more updates will come :)

These are omnidirectional wheels produced for robotics projects. They are designed to have the rollers mounted via M3 x 30mm bolts and the hub has been produced so that different shafts can be accommodated while not changing the overall design.

These are a work in progress, and are still being optimised for FDM printing. They are currently suitable for high-res FDM/FFM type printers and SLS/SLA/SLM/DLP type printers. Ideally I would like to have these work well while printing on a standard FDM/FFM printer operated by a user with minimal skills.

The provided model is compatible with http://www.dagurobot.com type motor/gearbox shafts e.g. http://www.dagurobot.com/goods.php?id=165

If you use this model, please do like/share/comment and let me know how you go with it. I am interested to see some printed parts from the 3D printing and robotics community.

If you would like advice on how to make a centre hub to suit a particular shaft, drop me a line and we can discuss the possibilities. It does not take long to modify the hub for another shaft size/arrangement.

This will require two 3/8-24 coupling nuts that are 1 1/8 inches long. Two one inch long 3/8-24 bolts, and two 3/8" washers. Additionally you may want to use two 3/8" Lugs to attach the Coax to each side.

You can use a grommet, and install a piece of Co-ax with a BNC connector on the end, or you can simply mount a BNC connector in the hole.

You can either print one arm in Red PLA, or print the Arm Ring in Red PLA, and install it on the arm that will be connected to the center conductor of the co-ax.

This, together with two of the Loading Coils, and either two of the Folding antennas, or two 9' long telescoping whip antenna's similar to the ones sold by Buddi-Pole, you can have a Portable 40M Dipole Antenna that you can rotate manually by rotating the Painter Pole.

I don't recommend this for continuous service. It is not designed to withstand being in the outdoors for long periods of time.

I started of with a need to store all of my coins. Then I realised I could print myself one, despite my beginner knowledge of Fusion 360. I measured all of the coins with my digital callipers and wrote all the dimensions down. Then made a sketch in Fusion with all the actual dimensions and drafted a rough shape.

After I came up with the shape and design of the sorter I offset the dimensions of the coins to give them some space in the sorter. Then I extruded the shape and gave it 3 dimensions.

Then I exported it as an stl file and printed it. 4 Hours later I fitted all the coins except the 50p and the 20p piece. It turns out that I inputed the dimensions in wrong so the two polygon shaped coins were 2 mm out.

Later I went back into Fusion 360 and enlarged the holes and re-printed it. 4 Hours later, I had the second prototype which was perfect. So I jumped back into Fusion, made some finishing touches and now I have my final model.

description.text:
UPDATE: After some use we've refined the design some more and it now works even better! I'll post a short 'how to' video soon.

Doing simple things that many able-bodied people take for granted can be a source of anxiety and depression for the elderly or disabled.

My elderly Aunt has tried a number of devices to help her do the simple act of putting socks on and off but hasn't found anything that worked well or was affordable so she asked me to design something for her. I didn't realise she was struggling so much. I suggest you consider asking this question as you also might be unaware of someone you care about struggling like this too.

So I took a few ideas and combined them and made some improvements and ended up with the 'Sock Helper'.

My printer is down waiting for repair parts to arrive but I hope to print it later this week and put up a short video of how to use it. Very simply, while seated you load a sock from the top and slide it down and then place it on the ground and slide your foot into the supported sock. The design incorporates a non-printed pole to lift and drop the 'Sock Helper'. This pole should be cut to around 60cm and can be made from a 20mm (3/4") PVC tube or a similar sized dowel or broom stick. The pole then inserts into the base where there is a hole to secure it with a screw.

There are two tabs on the end of the channel that are used to hook into the top of a sock so it can be easily slid off.

The design is also made for minimal supports and also has a printing brim to aid bed adhesion.

If you plan to print this in PLA then please make sure you don't use a brittle type of PLA because if you do the person using this is likely to brake it when pushing down by accident. See the 'print settings' section for suggested PLA and other filaments to use.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

i3 MK2S

Resolution:

0.25

Infill:

25%

Notes:

I used 4 perimeters and 25% infill as the person using this could put a fair bit of weight onto it by accident. The only place supports are needed is in the pole support hole.
UPDATE: After testing I found 3 perimeters is more than strong enough.

I now mainly use Simplyfy3D to slice for three main reasons;-

  1. the supports come away beautifully
  2. for items that rely on tight tolerances (like this case!) it prints the most accurate that I've used
  3. You can specify different print settings in a print so for sections with detail you can reduce layer height and for uniform sections you can increase it and get great looking prints done fast!

I suggest printing this in an improved PLA (see below) or other filament that's strong but doesn't warp too much. ABS is possible but only for those with lots of ABS experience and an appropriate setup for ABS as warping will likely ruin the print.

Beware: Not all PLA's are made equal.

Most of my prototypes and a good proportion of final prints are with an 'improved' PLA from Esun called PLA Plus (sometimes called pro) and it's tough and definitely not brittle and it's really cheap too. Some other moderately priced improved PLA's I've used are Filamentum, Prusa Brand & Colorfabb Economy PLA.

I haven't tried Hatchbox, Matterhackers, Taulman InPLA and Filaform Pro PLA but I hear some good things about them.

I also use a few better quality name brand PLA's for special one off jobs and these are quite a bit better than the Esun though up to triple the price. For the best looking prints with a fair bit better toughness than the Esun I use either Polymaker PolyMax PLA or ColorFabb PLA PHA. If excellent toughness and strength is a priority then the Polymaker PC Max polycarbonate is the one I'll always reach for and the finish is still good too.

You could also try finding some online filament reviews for strength comparisons.

!SEE HOW TO USE BELLOW!

This tool help you to find the centerpoint of your bed and calibrate your X and Y axis offsets to center your bed and make it aligned with your slicing program.

The cross in the middle should be placed in the middle of your bed in your slicing program and then once printed you can measure how much you need to offset your home position to have a common center. 4 of the straight edges intersect with the center of the part (not on radius side), etheir a calliper or a simple ruller can be used to determine the offsets you need to apply.

HOW TO USE:
1) Make sure part is centered to bed in slicing program, slice and export gcode.
2) Make sure bed leveling is good.
3) Ensure good bed adhesion (I used tape), because part needs to be held on bed while measuring.
4) Prepare printer
5) Print part (6-7 min)
6) DO NOT REMOVE PART FROM BED!
7) Measure distance from part center to all 4 bed edges.
8) Determine appropriated offsets that need to be applied by calculation axis differential.
9) Note offsets values and remove part.
10) Change offsets in firmware or slicer.
11) Redo step 1 to 7, if new center is good, keep it like this, otherwise redo procedure until you find an appropriate center.

description.text:
Summary

A double-roller spool holder that bolts on to the top of the I3 Plus frame.
Needs 4x 608 Bearings

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Notes:

Only part that needs supports is the rollers.

Hardware needed
  • 4x 608 bearings
  • Potentially 2x M5x6(?) bolts (If the stock spool holder bolts don't work for you)

You could probably leave the bolts out if needed, but it was designed to be bolted in.

What to Print
  • 2x frameSide
  • 2x rollerMk2
  • 2x axleNut
  • 2x axleBolt
  • leftMountBracket
  • rightMountBracket
  • 4x bearingShim (if needed)

The bearingShim is for if the sides of the rollers scrape on the frame, it will push the bearing out of the roller a bit.

Post Processing

I would definitely recommend sanding the inner area of the rollers, if nothing else to get rid of the layer start ridge.

Assembly

Pop the bearings into either side of the roller, and run a bolt through one side of the frame, the roller, and then the other side of the frame.

The side brackets should friction-fit into the sides of the frame. The flat bits of the brackets should go outwards from the sides of the frame.
The flat part of the notch should be on the inside of the frame.

I put the brackets on back-to-front, so you slip the bracket on to the back of the frame, and basically slide the bracket forward.

The right side bracket bolts in to the pre-drilled holes from the stock spool holder (I was able to use the original M5 bolts).

title: ANET A8 Y axis on ball bearings -  smooth and light !

description.text:
My ANET A8 had been delivered with a defective LM8UU linear bearing. it had a lot of friction, was very noisy and eventually lost 2 balls I found on the floor...

Moreover, the design of the Y axis is somewhat overconstrained with 4 linear bearings which are quite difficult to align properly. But , as the Y plate is quite flimsly, the idea to remove one LM8UU is not good... The good idea is to keep 3 points to guide the plane plus 1 another one using the flexibility of the Y plate to absorb this hyperstatic mount.

I then decided to design a parametric LM8UU based on a set of 3 standard ball bearings. Once installed this design reduces considerably friction and risks of misalignments.
You can see it working here: https://youtu.be/b4TINRRJZXQ

Another advantage is the gain in mass and inertia as 113 grams are recovered on the Y carriage, This is huge and will help to reduce Y-ghosting when fast printing !

both parts shall be printed without using supports.
But as there is a strong overhang on the upper part "washer" used to correctly center the ball bearing, there is systematically one small layer which is hanging once printed. You will need to gently file this to remove the hanging filament.

Holes for the rods are tight, you shall manually trim the holes using a 3mm drill tip. just perform one pass with the drill tip and go through the two parts of a single axis hole without removing the drill tip in order to remain perfectly aligned, it will be enough !

Once done you have to manufacture the axis. Use a 3mm steel rod that you will cut at

  • 12 to 13 mm for the axis of the top part (you'll need two of them)
  • 14 mm for the axis of the bottom part
    don't forget to deburr the small axis, try them first on a bearing to see if they fit...

Insert the ball bearing in their house, push them in position and check that the hole is properly aligned. Then insert the rod axis and push it through the ball bearing hole inside the plastic part. That's all, no screw, no play, nothing to trim and a perfect alignment of the bearings !
This mount with symetric crossing axis coupled with the printed washers on both sides of each ball bearing is very simple yet very efficient to ensure the bearings will keep overtime their correct orientation and centering. Moreover, my feeling is that, even printed in PLA, the supports will keep a good geometry over time... Let's see how they will age !

If you don't get 3mm rod, just look into your stock of nails, I'm ready to bet there are some long nails with an appropriate section ;-)

you will need 4 x 25mm M3 screws and nuts per bushing to mount them on the ANET.
Obviously, the hole are compatible with the ANET Y plate holes...

customizing ...

This thing should open in customizer (if it's not working, please download the latest version of openscad and just play with those lines :

// bearing model : 693zz (3x8x4) or 623zz (3x10x4)
bearing = "693zz"; // ["693zz", "623zz"]
This will allow you to select which bearing model to use. I would advise the 693zz which is smaller

// play with this value to trim the radius of the rod (negative value = reduce the radius)
trim = -0.05; //[-0.15,-0.1, -0.05, 0, 0.05, 0.1]
If after printing you find that there is too much play or not enough, you get options:

  • if too tight, add a paper washer between txo parts, or print the top part (the smaller) playing with the "trim" parameter. A positive value will enlarge the distance and thus give more room for the rod
  • if not enough tight : just sand the faces of the two parts in contact until you get the wished behaviour. Or use a negative value for "trim" parameter

// which thing ? top or bottom ?
part = "bottom"; // ["bottom", "top"]
this is just to tell openscad which part you want to print : top or bottom ?

// do you want intermediate nuts ?
nuts = "no" ; //["yes","no"]
The top part may be printed with footprints for some nuts so that the upper part remains in place even when removing the bottom one...

description.text: This part is specifically designed to make the moire/tree ring effect, caused by inaccurate microstepping or otherwise insufficient horizontal resolution, visible. Use this to test for it so that you can recalibrate to get rid of it. You probably won't need to worry about it unless you are trying to print layers .1mm or smaller. You don't get the full effect on the round pieces from the pictures, but check out the full-size (which is also upside-down for some reason) to get a better look: http://thingiverse-production.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/7e/1e/bb/0e/66/Photo_Jun_12_12_40_03.jpg

The effect will be easier to see when your vertical resolution gets better than your horizontal resolution. The print shown is at .1mm, and I calculated the rings to be caused by an effective horizontal resolution of .17mm (with proper calibration of my pololu drivers, it should be 1/16 of that). To make the effect most visible, print with shiny filament at .1mm or better vertical resolution. More information on this effect:
https://plus.google.com/u/0/105535247347788377245/posts/F8qQT2GB8q5

comments.text: Did you notice that this thing was posted in 2012? It was designed for use on a CupcakeCNC, which not only IS a really old printer (for any value of "old" that makes sense to use in this space), but also comes with stepper motors that are famous for being the most horribly-spec'd motors ever used in a 3D printer (IIRC, they were rated for 14V and were 35 ohms/phase, with inductance that was also, of course, way too high). Replacing those motors, even with different 200-step motors, could make a big difference. The stock stepper drivers were also horrible by today's standards (and IIRC only did half- or maybe quarter-stepping). In the early days of stepper extruders on those, it was also common to drive the extruder motor with PWM generated by a (Atmega168-based) extruder controller through a dual H-bridge chip rather than using a proper current-limiting stepper driver.

Notes:

Supports are needed as this should be printed with the rear of the case facing up just as the STL file appears. The reason it's not the other way around is that the detail on the back will likely be blemished by any supports.

I now mainly use Simplyfy3D to slice for three main reasons;-

  1. the supports come away beautifully and
  2. for items that rely on tight tolerances (like this case!) it prints the most accurate that I've used and
  3. You can specify different print settings in a print so for sections with detail you can reduce layer height and for uniform sections you can increase it and get great looking prints done fast!

I suggest printing with 4 perimeters and 25% infill as there's only a handful of grams of plastic in this so don't skimp.

I suggest printing this in an improved PLA (see below) or other filament that's strong and tough.

Beware: Not all PLA's are made equal.

Most of my prototypes and a good proportion of final prints are with an 'improved' PLA from Esun called PLA Plus (sometimes called pro) and it's tough and definitely not brittle and it's really cheap too. Some other moderately priced improved PLA's I've used are Filamentum, Prusa Brand & Colorfabb Economy PLA.

I haven't tried Hatchbox, Matterhackers, Taulman InPLA and Filaform Pro PLA but I hear some good things about them.

I also use a few better quality name brand PLA's for special one off jobs like phone cases and these are quite a bit better than the Esun though up to triple the price... though bare in mind this print in the pricey filament would still only cost a couple of bucks.

For the best looking prints with a fair bit better toughness than the Esun I use either Polymaker PolyMax PLA or ColorFabb PLA PHA. If excellent toughness and strength is a priority then the Polymaker PC Max polycarbonate is the one I'll always reach for and the finish is still good too.

Putting the case on.

Remember that even 'improved' PLA is not soft and rubbery like the urethane you get on phone cases so you need to take some more care than you do with other cases. But don't worry as I've taken mine off and on at least a dozen times and it's still working great so just follow these pointers.

First thing I do is make sure there aren't any stringers or blobs between the button cutouts and the 6 slots. It's normally good to go from there but you might find you might have to do a light sand to remove any artefacts.

  1. I start with the case flat on the table and then slide the bottom of your phone in starting around halfway down the case until the end is flush and the top of your phone is sticking out at an angle halfway up the phone.

  2. Now with both thumbs on the top sides of the phone and fingers along the case sides pick it up in place.

  3. I start on one side of the phone with the volume switches first and gently ease that side in first.

  4. Once in then a little more gently work the other side in next. If it catches at all just wiggle it a bit and it should eventually snap into place! And there you have it.

Notes:

Supports are needed as this should be printed with the rear of the case facing up just as the STL file appears. The reason it's not the other way around is that the detail on the back will likely be blemished by any supports.

I now mainly use Simplyfy3D to slice for three main reasons;-

  1. the supports come away beautifully and
  2. for items that rely on tight tolerances (like this case!) it prints the most accurate that I've used and
  3. You can specify different print settings in a print so for sections with detail you can reduce layer height and for uniform sections you can increase it and get great looking prints done fast!

I suggest printing with 4 perimeters and 25% infill as there's only a handful of grams of plastic in this so don't skimp.

I suggest printing this in an improved PLA (see below) or other filament that's strong and tough.

Beware: Not all PLA's are made equal.

Most of my prototypes and a good proportion of final prints are with an 'improved' PLA from Esun called PLA Plus (sometimes called pro) and it's tough and definitely not brittle and it's really cheap too. Some other moderately priced improved PLA's I've used are Filamentum, Prusa Brand & Colorfabb Economy PLA.

I haven't tried Hatchbox, Matterhackers, Taulman InPLA and Filaform Pro PLA but I hear some good things about them.

I also use a few better quality name brand PLA's for special one off jobs like phone cases and these are quite a bit better than the Esun though up to triple the price... though bare in mind this print in the pricey filament would still only cost a couple of bucks.

For the best looking prints with a fair bit better toughness than the Esun I use either Polymaker PolyMax PLA or ColorFabb PLA PHA. If excellent toughness and strength is a priority then the Polymaker PC Max polycarbonate is the one I'll always reach for and the finish is still good too.

Putting the case on.

Remember that even 'improved' PLA is not soft and rubbery like the urethane you get on phone cases so you need to take some more care than you do with other cases. But don't worry as I've taken mine off and on at least a dozen times and it's still working great so just follow these pointers.

First thing I do is make sure there aren't any stringers or blobs between the button cutouts and the 6 slots. It's normally good to go from there but you might find you might have to do a light sand to remove any artefacts.

  1. I start with the case flat on the table and then slide the bottom of your phone in starting around halfway down the case until the end is flush and the top of your phone is sticking out at an angle halfway up the phone.

  2. Now with both thumbs on the top sides of the phone and fingers along the case sides pick it up in place.

  3. I start on one side of the phone with the volume switches first and gently ease that side in first.

  4. Once in then a little more gently work the other side in next. If it catches at all just wiggle it a bit and it should eventually snap into place! And there you have it.

description.text:
This is part 2 of 2 for a set of brackets and hinges designed to modify the action of a grand piano's sustain pedal. This modification makes it possible for the player to press the pedal by sliding their right knee to the left.  
This thing contains the hinges for the aluminum bars that move the push-rod. The file can be modified in the customizer to accommodate aluminum bars of different widths and thicknesses.  
The reason behind this pedal-mod is that it is being developed for a very specific need. It is intended for a piano player who will be unable to put pressure on the balls of his feet for a while and, therefore, needs another mechanism to be able to continue to use the pedals during that time. The end goal is also to create a system that makes it nearly effortless to keep the pedal pressed to sustain long notes.  
This is under development so input, critique and ideas are welcome! :)
All of the holes for this design are sized for 4mm diameter bolts. A detailed explanation of this design can be found here: http://youtu.be/Jz0QdeYjpFk

I only encountered this porousity, if the PETG was not stored in low huminity before printing. I use big color indicator silica gel bags in paint buckets for storage of filaments.
Another approach would be thin coating the PETG vat with resin with a brush and uv curing it before applying the FEP foil. Should result in a water tight PETG vat.
Of course, PLA can be coated as well. ;)

comments.text: I also read a similar result by other users regarding PETG's porous surfaces. You may coat the surface, but I doubt the resin film firmly stick there reliably. I tried epoxy resin to cover PLA printed vat before, it worked fine for 5-10 times printing, but eventually they are peeled off. You may try different approaches, but I'd recommend PLA (maybe 2-3 wall perimeters and 50% or higher infill) for the best and least time consuming solution. :-)

description.text:
This is a small flashlight that i designed to print with the Ultimaker.
All you need is two AG12 button cells and a 5mm Led. Version 2 has an improved push switch. Have fun printing it!

-Calibrate your printer that the widht of the housing is 35mm(see picture)
-Put the negative led wire through the small hole down the bottom compartment.
-Be sure this wire lays flat to the bottom!!!
-Cut off the excessive wire
-Push the actual led in the hole
-Drop in two AG12 button cells negative polarity down
-Put the potitive wire in place
-Cut off the excessive wire
-Put the swith button in place
-Close the litte box by pushing it together.

It's a rounded blank luggage tag! Does it have lines? Nope. Does it have sharp corners? Nope. Does it have letters? Nope. It's a tag. For a bag. Kinda weird that I was unable to find anything this basic on Thingiverse, so I just made one. Upload it to Tinkercad or whatever and put some letters on it! I am making them for my kids' lunchboxes. Seriously, it's a tag.

Q: Can I make it bigger?
A: Sure. It's a tag.

Q: Can I make it out of some exotic plastic?
A: Yes. It's a tag. It will be as sturdy as the plastic. I am gonna use PLA.

Q: Hey, this has no words on it!
A: Yep, it's blank so you can put your name on it!

Q: Why is it rounded?
A: So it does not cut up your bag with its sharp edges.

A thin rail which attaches to a standard 3.5" hard drive for installation in a tower computer.  
I had a hard drive sitting on my desk for years I never installed because I lacked the rails to attach. Trying to find the rails for sale in stores near by was fruitless and searching online wasn't helping me find exactly what I needed. So I searching the Thingiverse for my needs. With a recently built Printrbot was sure to find what I needed and have it ready in moments! Well lo and behold, I couldn't find it here either. So I took to TinkerCAD to make the thing and share with you folks who may also be looking for this. It was modeled off the existing one in my machine.

Screws used are Flat Slotted 6-32 x 3/8" machine screws I found at the hardware store. These have a tapered head. You may want screws that fit flush so find any 6-32 x 3/8" screw and it should work.  
I don't believe there are any special printing instructions associated with this part.

title: Cherry pitter with a spring mechanism

description.text:
Our sour cherries (morello) were too small for the commercial cherry pitter and got mashed through its hole. If you try this on regular sweet cherries try scaling up 120% or so.

The version with a spring mechanism is actually useful if you need to pit a large amount of cherries, but the minimal hammer version is only a little better than a knife and is included merely because it is easier to print and illustrates the hammer mechanism.

Demo video: https://youtu.be/1LxzP1qJHak

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker 2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

50%

Notes:

The anvil and minimal hammer will probably print OK with almost any settings.

The hammer with a spring mechanism assumes a specific stiffness of the material (I used 50% infill PLA). The spring-hammer was trickier to print also otherwise as the tall towers were prone to lose adhesion when the print head bumped into them, so I added the side buttresses which you'll need to break off before use. Using a skirt probably helps too, but with the custom supports I got it to work without (67 °C bottom plate temperature) - try a skirt if you lose adhesion.

I added the small break-away part in the minimal hammer to give the hammer head time to cool between layers - without it was too bendy and got stuck to the print head.
